        {
            "id": "9350da328e1c43399012f",
            "questionText": "In a mass spectrometer, singly ionized neon atoms ($!$Ne^+$!$) are accelerated through a potential difference of $!$\\Delta V = 500\\ \\text{V}$!$ and then enter a uniform magnetic field of $!$B = 0.10\\ \\text{T}$!$. The magnetic field is perpendicular to the velocity of the ions. The radius of the circular path followed by the neon ions is measured to be $!$r = 0.05 \\text{ m}$!$. Given that the charge of an ion is $!$q = 1.60 \\times 10^{-19} \\text{ C}$!$, calculate the mass of a single neon ion in kilograms.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "d266beba961140c6ba326",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by considering how the kinetic energy gained by the neon ion relates to the potential difference it is accelerated through. Identify the correct equation that relates the kinetic energy $!$\\frac{1}{2}mv^2$!$ of the ion to the work done by the potential difference $!$q\\Delta V$!$.",
