        {
            "id": "d584e287b2eb4053a7218",
            "questionText": "Assuming a uniform electric field exists between the electrodes, how much work is done by the electric field to move a silver ion ($!$q = 1.602 \\times 10^{-19} \\text{ C}$!$) from the anode to the cathode, given that the potential difference is $!$\\Delta V = 12 \\text{ V}$!$ and the distance between the electrodes is $!$d = 0.1 \\text{ m}$!$?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "fbecefa6dbea4c3d91eed",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the relevant formula that relates the work done by an electric field to the charge and the potential difference. Which of the following formulas expresses this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
